post_cb({"27750818": {"ViewCount": "69", "Body": "<p>Considering that I'm compiler a 32 bits application (even though it doesn't change anything), does this code is safe?</p>\n<pre><code>cout &lt;&lt; (numeric_limits&lt;unsigned int&gt;::max() + 1) &lt;&lt; endl;\n</code></pre>\n<p>It prints \"0\" but does affect a bit of another variable? Let's say I have a byte(char) with the following bits and then I add 1: 1111 1111 (255). Would the result be \"1 0000 0000\" (256) and the cpu would only read the last 8 bits as my variable or would just reset the bit sequence?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "27750835", "Title": "Primitive types limit safety", "CreationDate": "2015-01-03T01:25:56.987", "Id": "27750818", "CommentCount": "2", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2015-01-03T02:50:00.007", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-03T01:48:08.890", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2924010", "Tags": "<c++><primitive-types>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_27750818_27750835_0": {"length": 14, "quality": 0.875, "section_id": 7213}}, "n3337": {"so_27750818_27750835_0": {"length": 16, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6957}}, "n4659": {"so_27750818_27750835_0": {"length": 14, "quality": 0.875, "section_id": 8722}}}, "27750835": {"Id": "27750835", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>C++ standard draft, \u00a73.9.1.4 requires that</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27750818_27750835_0\">Unsigned integers, declared unsigned, shall obey the laws of arithmetic modulo 2<sup>n</sup> where n is the number of bits in the value representation of that particular size of integer.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So the code in your question is required to output 0, as required by laws of modulo arithmetic.</p>\n<p>Note that the rule mentioned above doesn't apply to <code>char</code>, as it's not declared <code>unsigned</code> (you would need to use <code>unsigned char</code> instead). </p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "1012936", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-03T01:48:08.890", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2015-01-03T01:29:22.960", "ParentId": "27750818", "CommentCount": "1", "OwnerUserId": "1012936", "LastEditDate": "2015-01-03T01:48:08.890"}, "27750831": {"Id": "27750831", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Unsigned integer types obey the laws of arithmetic modulo 2^N. The result in this case will always be 0 and no other memory will be overwritten.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-03T01:28:55.887", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2015-01-03T01:28:55.887", "ParentId": "27750818", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "481267"}});